  "duration": 82.3379968,
  "text": " Hey guys, you never know where you're going to find something useful. I was reading one of Charles Polikman's books this morning. He's one of the top strength coaches in the world. He's got a lot of unique ideas. But he was talking about the principle of Kaizen. It's a Japanese term. Which kind of means getting a little bit better each day. Just a little bit. whatever it is you're doing. And that's going to have a compounding interest effect. So get a little bit better each day. Over time, you'll eventually be great at it. Pat Riley used that with basketball. He wanted all of his players to just get 1% better, 1% on one skill better each season, every couple months. And that adds up. Interestingly, there is There's no equivalent for the word Kaizen in English. So, but it's something we can take from the Japanese culture, something I strongly believe in. Get a little bit better each day, make a list each day, do it, complete it, and it's just going to be, the effects are going to be amazing over time. So the principle of Kaizen.",
